T 1139":"about 1115–after 1139","1115–1139":"1115–1139","1120–Female":"1120–Deceased","1140–Male":"1140–Deceased","1090–1114":"1090–1114","1095–Female":"1095–Deceased","1090":"1090","1139":"1139","1115":"1115","1114":"1114","AFT 1114":"after 1114","AFT 1139":"after 1139","1120":"1120","Abt 1115":"about 1115","1140":"1140","1095":"1095","Bradfield, Devonshire, England, United Kingdom":"Bradfield, Devon, England, United Kingdom","Bradfelle (Bradfield), Devon, England":"Bradfield, Devon, England, United Kingdom","England":"England, United Kingdom","Devon, England":"Devon, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert Bradfelle was born about 1115, in Bradfield, Devon, England, United Kingdom, his father, Robert Bradfelle, was 11113 and his mother, Mrs. Robert Bradfelle, was 22. He had at least 1 son with Mrs. Robert Bradfelle. He died after 1139, in Devon, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"Abt 1115–AFT 1139":"umbes 1115–pärast 1139","1115–1139":"1115–1139","1120–